tivist for many causes. “I read this intellectual biography of Françoise Héritier with great pleasure. Though highly regarded in France, she is not yet well known in English-language academic circles, but she certainly should be. This book will be a revelation to many anthropologists and feminist scholars.”—Adam Kuper, London School of Economics From the Forword by Michelle Perrot: I came to know her at the National Council for HIV, that she chaired from 1989 to 1994…. Her theoretical concerns were also crucial to the understanding of pandemics, but we did not then realise that HIV/AIDS was also a precursor and a warning of pandemics to come. She grasped the importance of conceptions of bodily ‘humours’—blood, semen, milk—that seemed to play a role in the horrific spread of an epidemic of which we knew nothing, except that it resulted in an appalling mortality rate, particularly among young men…. she was a remarkable chair, concerned to share her insights into the illness and to anchor—necessary—interventions within a framework that would be respectful of human rights.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mai 2023) 0aAnthropologistszFrancevBiography. 0aAnthropology. 0aEthnology. 0aFeministszFrancevBiography. 0aKinship. 0aSex role. 0aWomen anthropologistszFrancevBiography. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Social Scientists & Psychologists.2bisacsh  aClaude Lévi-Strauss.  aFrançoise Héritier.  aanthropologist.  aanthropology.  abiography.  afeminist scholars.  afeminist theory.  afeminist thought.  ahuman behavior.  asocial anthropology.  asociology.1 aPerrot, Michelle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBerghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2022z97831109976680 cprintz978180073332940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781800